   "notes": "<strong>1.</strong> In every atom, the positive charge and mass are densely concentrated at the centre of the atom forming its nucleus. More than 99.9% mass of the atom is concentrated in the nucleus.<br>\n<strong>2. Atomic Mass Unit</strong> (amu) The unit to express atomic masses is called atomic mass<br>\nunit. Atomic mass unit is defined as 1/12 th of the mass of carbon atom (C<sub>12</sub>).<br>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-175110 jetpack-lazy-image\" src=\"https://i1.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-1.png?resize=494%2C174&amp;ssl=1\" alt=\"Nuclei Class 12 Notes Chapter 13 Img 1\" data-recalc-dims=\"1\" data-lazy-srcset=\"https://i1.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-1.png?w=494&amp;ssl=1 494w, https://i1.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-1.png?resize=300%2C106&amp;ssl=1 300w\" data-lazy-sizes=\"(max-width: 494px) 100vw, 494px\" data-lazy-src=\"https://i1.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-1.png?resize=494%2C174&amp;is-pending-load=1#038;ssl=1\" srcset=\"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7\" width=\"494\" height=\"174\"><noscript><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-175110\" src=\"https://i1.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-1.png?resize=494%2C174&amp;ssl=1\" alt=\"Nuclei Class 12 Notes Chapter 13 Img 1\" srcset=\"https://i1.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-1.png?w=494&amp;ssl=1 494w, https://i1.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-1.png?resize=300%2C106&amp;ssl=1 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 494px) 100vw, 494px\" data-recalc-dims=\"1\" width=\"494\" height=\"174\"></noscript><br>\n<strong>3. Composition of Nucleus</strong> The composition of a nucleus can be described by using the following terms and symbols.<br>\n<strong>(i) Atomic Number Z</strong> Atomic number of an element is the number of protons present inside the nucleus of an atom of the element.<br>\nAtomic number = Number of protons = Number of electrons<br>\n<strong>(ii) Mass Number A</strong> Mass number of an element is the total number of protons and neutrons inside the atomic nucleus of the element.<br>\nMass number = Number of protons + Number of neutrons = Number of electrons + Number of neutrons i.e. A=Z.+ N"
