   "notes": "<strong>10. Mean Life/Average Life</strong> Average life of a radioactive element can be obtained by calculating the total life time of all the atoms of the radioactive element and dividing it by the total number of atoms present initially in the sample of the element.<br>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-175115 jetpack-lazy-image\" src=\"https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-6.png?resize=491%2C246&amp;ssl=1\" alt=\"Nuclei Class 12 Notes Chapter 13 Img 6\" data-recalc-dims=\"1\" data-lazy-srcset=\"https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-6.png?w=491&amp;ssl=1 491w, https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-6.png?resize=300%2C150&amp;ssl=1 300w\" data-lazy-sizes=\"(max-width: 491px) 100vw, 491px\" data-lazy-src=\"https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-6.png?resize=491%2C246&amp;is-pending-load=1#038;ssl=1\" srcset=\"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7\" width=\"491\" height=\"246\"><noscript><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-175115\" src=\"https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-6.png?resize=491%2C246&amp;ssl=1\" alt=\"Nuclei Class 12 Notes Chapter 13 Img 6\" srcset=\"https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-6.png?w=491&amp;ssl=1 491w, https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-6.png?resize=300%2C150&amp;ssl=1 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 491px) 100vw, 491px\" data-recalc-dims=\"1\" width=\"491\" height=\"246\"></noscript><br>\n<strong>11. Time required to decay from N<sub>0</sub> to N</strong><br>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-175116 jetpack-lazy-image\" src=\"https://i1.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-7.png?resize=413%2C296&amp;ssl=1\" alt=\"Nuclei Class 12 Notes Chapter 13 Img 7\" data-recalc-dims=\"1\" data-lazy-srcset=\"https://i1.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-7.png?w=413&amp;ssl=1 413w, https://i1.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-7.png?resize=300%2C215&amp;ssl=1 300w\" data-lazy-sizes=\"(max-width: 413px) 100vw, 413px\" data-lazy-src=\"https://i1.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-7.png?resize=413%2C296&amp;is-pending-load=1#038;ssl=1\" srcset=\"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7\" width=\"413\" height=\"296\"><noscript><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-175116\" src=\"https://i1.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-7.png?resize=413%2C296&amp;ssl=1\" alt=\"Nuclei Class 12 Notes Chapter 13 Img 7\" srcset=\"https://i1.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-7.png?w=413&amp;ssl=1 413w, https://i1.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-7.png?resize=300%2C215&amp;ssl=1 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 413px) 100vw, 413px\" data-recalc-dims=\"1\" width=\"413\" height=\"296\"></noscript><br>\n<strong>12. Decay Constant</strong> The radioactive decay constant may be defined as the reciprocal of the time during which the number of atoms in a radioactive substance reduces to 36.8% of their initial number.<br>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-175117 jetpack-lazy-image\" src=\"https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-8.png?resize=452%2C152&amp;ssl=1\" alt=\"Nuclei Class 12 Notes Chapter 13 Im