  {
   "notes": "<strong>13. Radioactive Displacement Law</strong> The law of radioactive displacement is also known as Fajan’s and Soddy law. This law describes which chemical element and isotope is created during the particular type of radioactive decay.<br>\n<strong>(i) α- Decay</strong> In α-decay, the mass number of the product nucleus is four less than that of decaying nucleus while the atomic number decreases by two.<br>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-175118 jetpack-lazy-image\" src=\"https://i1.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-9.png?resize=527%2C168&amp;ssl=1\" alt=\"Nuclei Class 12 Notes Chapter 13 Img 9\" data-recalc-dims=\"1\" data-lazy-srcset=\"https://i1.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-9.png?w=527&amp;ssl=1 527w, https://i1.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-9.png?resize=300%2C96&amp;ssl=1 300w\" data-lazy-sizes=\"(max-width: 527px) 100vw, 527px\" data-lazy-src=\"https://i1.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-9.png?resize=527%2C168&amp;is-pending-load=1#038;ssl=1\" srcset=\"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7\" width=\"527\" height=\"168\"><noscript><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-175118\" src=\"https://i1.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-9.png?resize=527%2C168&amp;ssl=1\" alt=\"Nuclei Class 12 Notes Chapter 13 Img 9\" srcset=\"https://i1.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-9.png?w=527&amp;ssl=1 527w, https://i1.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-9.png?resize=300%2C96&amp;ssl=1 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 527px) 100vw, 527px\" data-recalc-dims=\"1\" width=\"527\" height=\"168\"></noscript><br>\n<strong>(ii) β-Decay</strong> In β-decay, the mass number of product nucleus remains same but atomic number increases or decreases by one.<br>\nIn beta-minus decay (β<sup>–</sup> ),an electron and an antineutrino are created and emitted from the nucleus via the reaction given below:<br>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-175119 jetpack-lazy-image\" src=\"https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-10.png?resize=502%2C196&amp;ssl=1\" alt=\"Nuclei Class 12 Notes Chapter 13 Img 10\" data-recalc-dims=\"1\" data-lazy-srcset=\"https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-10.png?w=502&amp;ssl=1 502w, https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-10.png?resize=300%2C117&amp;ssl=1 300w\" data-lazy-sizes=\"(max-width: 502px) 100vw, 502px\" data-lazy-src=\"https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-10.png?resize=502%2C196&amp;is-pending-load=1#038;ssl=1\" srcset=\"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7\" width=\"502\" height=\"196\"><noscript><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-175119\" src=\"https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-10.png?resize=502%2C196&amp;ssl=1\" alt=\"Nuclei Class 12 Notes Chapter 13 Img 10\" srcset=\"https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-10.png?w=502&amp;ssl=1 502w, https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-10.png?resize=300%2C117&amp;ssl=1 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 502px) 100vw, 502px\" data-recalc-dims=\"1\" width=\"502\" height=\"196\"></noscript><br>\nIn beta-plus decay (β<sup>+</sup>), a positron and a neutrino are created and emitted from the nucleus via the reaction given below:<br>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-175120 jetpack-lazy-image\" src=\"https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-11.png?resize=510%2C183&amp;ssl=1\" alt=\"Nuclei Class 12 Notes Chapter 13 Img 11\" data-recalc-dims=\"1\" data-lazy-srcset=\"https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-11.png?w=510&amp;ssl=1 510w, https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-11.png?resize=300%2C108&amp;ssl=1 300w\" data-lazy-sizes=\"(max-width: 510px) 100vw, 510px\" data-lazy-src=\"https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-11.png?resize=510%2C183&amp;is-pending-load=1#038;ssl=1\" srcset=\"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7\" width=\"510\" height=\"183\"><noscript><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-175120\" src=\"https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-11.png?resize=510%2C183&amp;ssl=1\" alt=\"Nuclei Class 12 Notes Chapter 13 Img 11\" srcset=\"https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-11.png?w=510&amp;ssl=1 510w, https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-11.png?resize=300%2C108&amp;ssl=1 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 510px) 100vw, 510px\" data-recalc-dims=\"1\" width=\"510\" height=\"183\"></noscript><br>\n<strong>(iii) γ-Decay</strong> A γ- ray is emitted when a or β-decay results in a daughter nucleus in an excited state. Atom then returns to ground state by a single photon transition or successive transitions involving more than one photon.<br>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-175121 jetpack-lazy-image\" src=\"https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-12.png?resize=353%2C143&amp;ssl=1\" alt=\"Nuclei Class 12 Notes Chapter 13 Img 12\" data-recalc-dims=\"1\" data-lazy-srcset=\"https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-12.png?w=353&amp;ssl=1 353w, https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-12.png?resize=300%2C122&amp;ssl=1 300w\" data-lazy-sizes=\"(max-width: 353px) 100vw, 353px\" data-lazy-src=\"https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-12.png?resize=353%2C143&amp;is-pending-load=1#038;ssl=1\" srcset=\"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7\" width=\"353\" height=\"143\"><noscript><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-175121\" src=\"https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-12.png?resize=353%2C143&amp;ssl=1\" alt=\"Nuclei Class 12 Notes Chapter 13 Img 12\" srcset=\"https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-12.png?w=353&amp;ssl=1 353w, https://i2.wp.com/www.cbselabs.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Nuclei-Class-12-Notes-Chapter-13-Img-12.png?resize=300%2C122&amp;ssl=1 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 353px) 100vw, 353px\" data-recalc-dims=\"1\" width=\"353\" height=\"143\"></noscript>"
